context: By the 1860s <b5_0>the <a0_0>Kingdom of Prussia and the Austrian Empire<b5_0/><a0_0/> were the two most powerful nations dominated by German-speaking elites. Both sought to expand their <a3_0>influence and territory<a3_0/>. <a4_0>The Austrian Empire<a4_0/> – like <b6_0>the Holy Roman Empire<b6_0/> – was a multi-ethnic state, but German-speaking people there did not have an absolute numerical majority; the creation of the <b7_0>Austro-Hungarian Empire<b7_0/> was one result of the growing nationalism of other ethnicities especially the Hungarians. Prussia under Otto von Bismarck would ride on the coat-tails of nationalism to unite all of modern-day Germany. <b8_0>The German Empire<b8_0/> ("Second Reich") was created in <a1_0>1871<a1_0/> following the proclamation of Wilhelm I as <a2_0>head of a union of German-speaking states<a2_0/>, while disregarding millions of its non-German subjects who desired self-determination from German rule.
